it.polimi.checker.intersection

Class IntersectionTransitionBuilder

  • java.lang.Object
    • it.polimi.checker.intersection.IntersectionTransitionBuilder

  • public class IntersectionTransitionBuilder
extends Object
    Defines an rule that specifies how the transitions of the intersection automaton are generated starting from the transition of the model and the claim.
    The rule specifies that the transition of the model can be performed only if it satisfies the conditions specified in the claim. Or, the transition of the claim can be performed if the model is in a black box state
    Author:
    Claudio Menghi

    • Method Detail

      • getIntersectionTransition

        public Transition getIntersectionTransition(Transition modelTransition,
                                            Transition claimTransition)
        Given two transitions, one of the model and one of the claim, creates the intersection transitions. Throws an InternalError if the two transitions are not compatible, i.e., they cannot be fired together. To check whether two transitions can be fired together run the is compatible method.
        Parameters:
        modelTransition - the transition of the model to be fired
        claimTransition - is the transition of the claim to be fired
        Returns:
        a transition that is the synchronous execution between the modelTransition and the claimTransition
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if the transition of the model or the claim is null
        InternalError - if the two transitions are not compatible

      • isCompatible

        public boolean isCompatible(Transition modelTransition,
                            Transition claimTransition)
        checks whether the transition of the model and the transition of the claim are compatible, i.e., it is possible to fire the transition of the model and the claim synchronously
        Parameters:
        modelTransition - is the transition of the model to be fired
        claimTransition - is the transition of the claim to be fired
        Returns:
        true if the label of the transition of model satisfies the label of the transition of the claim 1) returns true if the stuttering character is contained both on the model and the claim label 2) returns true if the Sigma proposition is 3) returns false if there is a claim proposition that is negated, but the proposition is contained in the labels of the model 4) returns false if there is a claim proposition that is not negated, but the proposition is not contained inside the set of propositions of the model
        Throws:
        NullPointerException - if the transition of the model or the transition of the claim is null
